Research benchmark datasets and evaluation methodologies for code smell detectors. The two most important questions are: what ground-truth datasets exist for evaluating code smell detection precision and recall, and what precision and recall do state-of-the-art tools actually achieve? Cover the following datasets: ManySStuBs4J for simple bugs in Java, Defects4J as a reproducible bug benchmark, the Palomba et al. code smell oracle datasets (god class, data class, feature envy, long method), and the Fontana et al. oracle for antipatterns in open-source Java systems. For each dataset, document what smells are labeled, how many instances, which projects, and whether it has been reused and validated by later work. Research the detection tools evaluated against these benchmarks: JDeodorant, PMD, Checkstyle, SonarQube, iPlasma, and Palomba's own HIST tool. Document the precision and recall numbers from the most rigorous comparative studies. Also research whether smell detectors trained or tuned on Java generalize to other languages, and what cross-language evaluation datasets exist. Finally, cover the inter-rater reliability problem in code smell research: how much do human developers agree on whether a given piece of code has a smell, and how does that agreement ceiling bound the achievable precision of automated detectors?
